1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:08,420
Hello everyone, welcome to Octothorpe episode 1, a new podcast brought to you by boredom and self-isolation.

2
00:00:08,420 --> 00:00:12,960
I'm John Coxon, I'm a fan from the UK and I am joined by...

3
00:00:12,960 --> 00:00:16,100
Hi, I'm Alison Scott, I'm also a fan from the UK.

4
00:00:16,100 --> 00:00:21,940
Hello, I'm Liz, I'm also a fan from the UK but I currently live in Thailand.

5
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:36,080
We've decided to do a podcast about fandom from a British perspective and we're going to be talking about a few topics today in a kind of first episode stab at podcasting.

6
00:00:36,080 --> 00:00:42,520
On the morning we record, it's the day after the Eastercon cancelled.

7
00:00:42,520 --> 00:00:51,340
So Eastercon is the British National Science Fiction Convention and Concentric 2020 was to be held in Birmingham this year.

8
00:00:51,480 --> 00:00:55,040
But it has been cancelled as a result of COVID-19.

9
00:00:55,040 --> 00:01:01,660
Now Alison was the fan guest of honour and I think all three of us are keen Eastercon fans.

10
00:01:01,660 --> 00:01:04,780
How are you guys reacting to the cancellation?

11
00:01:04,780 --> 00:01:08,320
Well, I am, as they say, gutted.

12
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:17,320
I was obviously hugely looking forward to Eastercon anyway because it was the Eastercon and it's my favourite convention of the whole year.

13
00:01:17,780 --> 00:01:22,520
But also because I was going to be fan guest and I was very much looking forward to that.

14
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:25,640
And I had a lot of ideas about fun things we could do.

15
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:31,200
And so now I guess we're going to spend our spring doing fun things indoors instead.

16
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:36,660
And I'm also, I think, worried because it makes me wonder, will we have an Eastercon next year?

17
00:01:36,660 --> 00:01:38,060
Will we have more conventions?

18
00:01:38,060 --> 00:01:42,220
Is this it for the practice of travelling around the world and meeting our friends?

19
00:01:42,220 --> 00:01:46,360
So I've been assuming it was going to be cancelled for at least two or three weeks.

20
00:01:46,360 --> 00:01:54,700
We were just waiting on the final, you know, legal coverage so that it could be cancelled without the committee being at a huge financial loss.

21
00:01:54,700 --> 00:02:00,160
I mean, I'm selfishly a little bit glad because I wasn't going to make it this year.

22
00:02:00,160 --> 00:02:06,660
And I really wanted to go in the year that Alison was fan guest of honour because I think it would be hilarious and fun.

23
00:02:06,660 --> 00:02:08,680
May never happen again.

24
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:12,220
I like hanging out with Alison because she's such a ray of sunshine.

25
00:02:12,220 --> 00:02:16,080
I'm assuming that there will be future Eastercons.

26
00:02:16,080 --> 00:02:22,840
Although, of course, I have, you know, something of a vested interest in global aviation still existing.

27
00:02:22,840 --> 00:02:28,660
Because I would at some point like to return to the UK and not live the rest of my life in Thailand.

28
00:02:28,660 --> 00:02:34,260
But that may be a deeper question than the cancellation of Eastercons, I feel.

29
00:02:34,260 --> 00:02:46,620
I think Alison's point about whether this will presage the changing of how we do travel and socialising is a really interesting question.

30
00:02:46,620 --> 00:02:52,040
And probably would take longer than we have on this podcast to properly answer.

31
00:02:52,040 --> 00:03:04,400
But one of the things I have seen a lot in my professional capacity as someone who goes to science conferences is people discussing whether or not conferences are still a viable thing to do.

32
00:03:04,620 --> 00:03:20,320
But from my perspective, conventions are so much about the social aspect that I kind of feel like after all this has gone away again, we're going to be even more keen to go and see our friends because we're going to have missed out on that for so long.

33
00:03:20,320 --> 00:03:26,920
So do you two think that this will be a portent of the end of conventions?

34
00:03:26,920 --> 00:03:34,040
Or do you think it's going to be a reason to continue conventioning with even more vim and vigour?

35
00:03:34,320 --> 00:03:40,500
I think I should clarify that when I said may never happen again, I was referring to my never being guest of honour again.

36
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:52,820
But I promise to do everything like being guest of honour, like staying up too late and drinking in the bar and meeting everyone at the Eastercon and all of that stuff anyway.

37
00:03:52,820 --> 00:03:55,620
I'm sure we're going to have more conventions.

38
00:03:55,620 --> 00:03:57,280
I'm certain of it.

39
00:03:57,280 --> 00:04:03,860
I think that everyone will be well ready for a convention once we're all vaccinated against this pandemic.

40
00:04:04,020 --> 00:04:06,420
And I'm sure there won't ever be another pandemic.

41
00:04:06,420 --> 00:04:07,260
Isn't that right, Liz?

42
00:04:07,260 --> 00:04:08,720
Oh, yeah, absolutely.

43
00:04:08,720 --> 00:04:09,980
This is this is the only one.

44
00:04:09,980 --> 00:04:11,280
This is never going to happen again.

45
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:16,780
Viruses, you know, don't jump over from, you know, animals on a regular basis or anything like that.

46
00:04:18,120 --> 00:04:27,540
Is this the point where I, you know, inform our listeners that I work on tropical infectious diseases and so I might have a slightly skewed view on global pandemics?

47
00:04:28,020 --> 00:04:33,660
Yeah, I think I think I think of the three of us, you are the one that is most similar to an expert.

48
00:04:33,660 --> 00:04:37,060
So that's probably relevant information.

49
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:43,540
I think because we've been having conversations about Eastercon up to the cancellation.

50
00:04:43,540 --> 00:04:54,840
And I think most people assumed that it would eventually be cancelled once the government announced that mass gatherings and pubs and restaurants were no longer going to be allowed.

51
00:04:54,980 --> 00:05:00,700
It was just a question of when they would do that and therefore when the cancellation would come.

52
00:05:00,700 --> 00:05:04,920
I think to go back to your point earlier, Liz, I was also expecting this to happen.

53
00:05:04,920 --> 00:05:14,080
I'm very relieved that the government has come out and taken steps that allow pubs and restaurants and places like that to close.

54
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:20,300
Because I think until a couple of days ago, that was something that was very difficult for a small business like that to countenance.

55
00:05:20,300 --> 00:05:23,720
And obviously the Hilton being a small business, that's important.

56
00:05:23,720 --> 00:05:24,520
Yes. Yes.

57
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:27,500
All my sympathies are definitely with the Hilton on this one.

58
00:05:27,820 --> 00:05:33,800
My sympathies rest with the committee and with the management of this hotel.

59
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:39,300
It's clear that the hotel didn't feel they were in a position to cancel for some time.

60
00:05:39,300 --> 00:05:43,080
And I'm not privileged to any particular information here.

61
00:05:43,080 --> 00:05:51,040
The committee did say, please don't talk about what might happen as if you were a member of the committee.

62
00:05:51,320 --> 00:06:00,580
So I think we could talk about what might happen with absolutely no knowledge whatsoever and making it completely clear we have nothing to do with the committee.

63
00:06:00,580 --> 00:06:16,500
And I would like to see us spend part of our Easter weekend getting together, having some online discussion groups and Zoom chats and Zoom parties, which are just like room parties, except with social distancing.

64
00:06:17,100 --> 00:06:47,080
With a pun.

65
00:06:47,080 --> 00:06:50,380
Do you think that will be something that gets organised as a grassroots thing?

66
00:06:50,380 --> 00:06:52,740
Or have you seen people start to talk about that?

67
00:06:53,060 --> 00:06:57,900
I've seen people on Twitter starting to discuss it, but nothing concrete yet.

68
00:06:58,040 --> 00:07:05,020
I think there's also a feeling that maybe we need to give the committee a few days to kind of process that, yes, the convention is actually cancelled.

69
00:07:05,020 --> 00:07:08,780
All their effort is not going to result in an event.

70
00:07:08,780 --> 00:07:10,440
And to decide whether they're going to have a few days to do something.

71
00:07:10,440 --> 00:07:16,280
And to decide whether they feel like they can redirect that into trying to do something online involving some of what they had planned for the actual event.

72
00:07:16,280 --> 00:07:26,920
Or whether they'd rather sort of hand it over to fandom and say, sorry, we cannot do anything in person this weekend, but we give you our blessing to organise your own social gatherings online.

73
00:07:27,160 --> 00:07:37,820
I have one more thought about Eastercon, which is that I'm very glad that in the great game of Pass the Parcel that is running the Eastercon, the parcel didn't land when I was chair.

74
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:44,020
So I have nothing but sympathy for this committee and what they're having to put up with now and deal with.

75
00:07:44,020 --> 00:07:47,420
And I just, all my heart goes out to them, really.

76
00:07:47,420 --> 00:07:56,000
I think that as a fandom, we need to give the ConCom the space to do what they want to do.

77
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:05,620
If they still see the Easter weekend as something they want to head up and organise, even in an online capacity, then I'm thrilled and I'll be super behind them.

78
00:08:05,940 --> 00:08:16,980
But if they are super crushed by the fact that all this has happened and they just want to go and kind of have some time, then I think that's another thing we have to be super supportive of, like in either direction.

79
00:08:16,980 --> 00:08:21,620
Because I can't imagine how stressful the last month must have been for that convention committee.

80
00:08:21,620 --> 00:08:22,540
It must have been awful.

81
00:08:22,540 --> 00:08:35,800
Alison, as a former Eastercon chair, can you give us a little bit of an idea of what the Eastercon committee is financially on the hook for every year and the sort of risks that you take when you do commit to running one?

82
00:08:35,800 --> 00:08:41,440
Well, I think that the primary problem here will be twofold.

83
00:08:41,440 --> 00:08:53,880
The first is that they will have given a commitment to the hotel that, pending disasters of which this is clearly one, they will have taken a number of rooms in the hotel, quite a large number of rooms.

84
00:08:54,660 --> 00:08:59,160
And then the second thing is that they will have guaranteed a food and drink spend for the hotel.

85
00:09:00,560 --> 00:09:10,500
So you say, not only we will bring in soever many people to your hotel this weekend, but also they will eat and drink a lot of food and drink.

86
00:09:10,500 --> 00:09:17,960
And that's how you get the rate on the conference space is by promising to spend a very large amount of money on food and drink.

87
00:09:19,240 --> 00:09:23,120
That will have been considerably more than the cost of the cost of the hotel.

88
00:09:23,120 --> 00:09:30,640
The government mandating that restaurants and bars close was the, I think, final straw.

89
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:39,500
The impression I get from the convention announcement is that the hotel would have been unable to let people eat or drink in the hotel common areas.

90
00:09:40,140 --> 00:09:49,920
And so as soon as that happens, you have real trouble with your ability as a hotel to fulfill your contract from that kind of holding a big event perspective.

91
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:58,760
So I think that's why the cancellation happened now, because it was that that meant it became completely unworkable.

92
00:09:58,760 --> 00:10:07,680
I can't remember what the typical food and drink spend for an Easter con is, but I know it's usually five figures.

93
00:10:08,520 --> 00:10:14,520
I'd expect them to have a figure for a guarantee for food and drink in the high five figures.

94
00:10:14,520 --> 00:10:17,240
Which is a mad amount of money.

95
00:10:17,240 --> 00:10:19,560
So there's not...

96
00:10:19,560 --> 00:10:21,300
Have you seen how much beer costs?

97
00:10:21,300 --> 00:10:22,700
Yes.

98
00:10:22,700 --> 00:10:25,340
At five pounds a pint, it doesn't take a lot.

99
00:10:25,340 --> 00:10:26,020
That's true.

100
00:10:26,020 --> 00:10:26,700
That's true.

101
00:10:26,700 --> 00:10:30,860
When I was an undergraduate, I used to complain about that very vocally.

102
00:10:30,860 --> 00:10:34,240
Strangely, now I earn more money, I complain less.

103
00:10:34,240 --> 00:10:37,440
There's no seated Easter con for 2021.

104
00:10:38,020 --> 00:10:39,660
There's not an Easter con constitution.

105
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:46,600
If we've got any US listeners who are used to Robert's Rules of Order and Worcester's Constitutions and all of these things,

106
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:56,860
the Easter con is an anarchic collective of like-minded fans who sort of run conventions by gentleman's agreement as much as by anything else.

107
00:10:56,860 --> 00:11:01,700
And so there's not any provision in any written document for what happens now.

108
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:06,800
So how do we select the next Easter con and how does all that work?

109
00:11:06,800 --> 00:11:17,620
When you say that Easter con is run by a collective of like-minded fans, if enough former chairs of Easter con put their weight behind a proposal that comes forward,

110
00:11:17,620 --> 00:11:20,060
it will just be agreed by a claim.

111
00:11:20,060 --> 00:11:21,720
I just don't think there's a...

112
00:11:21,720 --> 00:11:27,060
I think this is much more of a problem in the minds of rules nerds than it is in practice.

113
00:11:27,060 --> 00:11:30,140
I also don't think people are going to be lining up to run the Easter con.

114
00:11:30,480 --> 00:11:33,400
You know, it would be a problem if you had a lot of contested bids.

115
00:11:35,340 --> 00:11:46,280
No, I think it's going to be very difficult for whoever does step up and decide they want to run one next year because they really won't be able to make any concrete plans for quite a while at this point.

116
00:11:46,280 --> 00:11:49,800
They can try and find a hotel, but they can't go and visit a hotel.

117
00:11:49,800 --> 00:11:53,520
They can't really make any commitments to guests or anything like that.

118
00:11:53,520 --> 00:12:01,580
I mean, I think you're probably looking at least the summer, if not early autumn, before we even know if we'll be able to go and have an Easter con next year.

119
00:12:01,820 --> 00:12:03,420
So I think it's going to be a very difficult task.

120
00:12:03,420 --> 00:12:09,340
And frankly, if someone steps up to do it, then I will vote for them wholeheartedly.

121
00:12:09,340 --> 00:12:18,180
The most recent analogue is probably the 2007 Easter con, which was held in Chester after the Liverpool Easter con folded.

122
00:12:18,180 --> 00:12:27,240
And that, I think, was a case where the convention was organised on about six months' notice, if I recall correctly.

123
00:12:27,360 --> 00:12:32,740
I think convoy folded in the summer and the convention was in March 2007.

124
00:12:32,740 --> 00:12:34,800
And so it can be done.

125
00:12:34,800 --> 00:12:41,800
I don't know whether it will be the size of Easter con you would expect, because obviously Chester was very small for an Easter con.

126
00:12:41,800 --> 00:12:46,680
And it might be that if there's only a six-month lead-up, you do get a hit to attendance.

127
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:53,220
But last time something even remotely similar to this happened, we still had an Easter con, even if it was a much smaller one.

128
00:12:53,220 --> 00:12:55,520
So I'm hopeful that this is all resolved.

129
00:12:55,520 --> 00:13:02,840
And I think Alison's point is right, that this is much more a problem in the minds of rules nerds than it is in real life.

130
00:13:02,940 --> 00:13:08,860
Because if enough people want there to be an Easter con, there'll be an Easter con, regardless of any other considerations.

131
00:13:08,860 --> 00:13:10,440
I think that's true.

132
00:13:10,440 --> 00:13:18,480
I mean, I wonder how much of the 2020 Easter con the committee might want to try and roll forward into 2021.

133
00:13:18,480 --> 00:13:22,100
Because presumably there's been a lot of planning done already.

134
00:13:22,100 --> 00:13:24,460
A lot of organisations have been done.

135
00:13:24,460 --> 00:13:29,880
It's possible that some of it can just be sort of jumped forward a year if they wanted to go again for next year.

136
00:13:29,880 --> 00:13:33,440
But I would also understand if they really want to take a break.

137
00:13:33,440 --> 00:13:46,220
I think my question would be that we compare this to 2007, but it's not really the same situation as 2007, I think, because, you know, it's a completely different background.

138
00:13:46,220 --> 00:13:46,700
Yeah.

139
00:13:46,700 --> 00:13:57,120
But the question is, it seems like Easter con has rolled along as a sort of very loose collective gentleman's agreement, different from year to year, for a long time.

140
00:13:57,120 --> 00:14:03,380
And possibly, actually, it's a ticking time bomb we have been passing along for a while and happens to explode in 2020.

141
00:14:03,380 --> 00:14:08,520
Do you think this will lead to a long term change in how we organise them?

142
00:14:08,520 --> 00:14:12,580
I think this is a great topic for another episode of Octothorpe.

143
00:14:12,580 --> 00:14:16,360
Tune in next time when we talk about Wither Easter con.

144
00:14:16,360 --> 00:14:20,380
I think that is a long discussion and I think it's a good question.

145
00:14:20,380 --> 00:14:24,200
And I think we will come back to it in future episodes.

146
00:14:24,200 --> 00:14:27,680
And we would love our listeners to write in with their thoughts.

147
00:14:27,680 --> 00:14:37,220
So on the subject of Easter con being cancelled, on the topic of the fan funds, Michael Lowry, who is this year's TAF delegate, has cancelled his trip.

148
00:14:38,160 --> 00:14:45,480
Unfortunately, TAF, which is the transatlantic fan fund, has enough money in the bank that it can run another trip next year.

149
00:14:45,480 --> 00:14:49,380
And this shouldn't be too much of a problem in the perspective of the fund.

150
00:14:49,380 --> 00:14:55,900
But obviously, the other fan funds, such as the Down Under fan fund and the Going Under fan fund, will be affected.

151
00:14:55,900 --> 00:15:02,820
And projects like Con or Bust, which gets people of colour to conventions, may also be impacted.

152
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:08,020
Do you two have any thoughts about how this is going to affect that kind of thing?

153
00:15:08,020 --> 00:15:11,200
Fair, full disclosure, I am one of this year's guff candidates.

154
00:15:11,200 --> 00:15:18,520
So I am running to be the fan who goes from Europe to New Zealand for the New Zealand Worldcon.

155
00:15:18,520 --> 00:15:22,020
I think at this point, the New Zealand Worldcon must be in doubt.

156
00:15:22,020 --> 00:15:26,740
July time, I don't see how it's going to happen, but it might do.

157
00:15:27,080 --> 00:15:34,080
And I particularly wanted to run this year because it's the first year after my youngest child turned 18.

158
00:15:34,080 --> 00:15:42,240
So I can actually go off and party in New Zealand and Australia for weeks on end without having family responsibilities.

159
00:15:42,980 --> 00:15:46,400
But I'd be very happy to run for guff at some future date.

160
00:15:46,400 --> 00:15:54,660
The guff has always found it harder to raise money than taff has, just because the expense of a trip is very much greater.

161
00:15:54,660 --> 00:15:59,680
And the number of fans in Australia and New Zealand is slightly smaller.

162
00:16:00,440 --> 00:16:09,080
I think guff this year, I think it's going to be cancelled because we won't be sure if there is a Worldcon in time for anyone to seriously plan.

163
00:16:09,080 --> 00:16:18,720
And also, I think the finances are so difficult, especially given that there are a lot of teams wanting to run for guff this year,

164
00:16:18,720 --> 00:16:24,440
that it might be reckless to make any kind of concrete reservations that can't be cancelled for full refunds,

165
00:16:24,440 --> 00:16:29,720
because you might just sort of take out all of the guff reserves and then you won't be able to run again.

166
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:36,080
I also think, speaking as someone, you know, in a country I live in, which I'm not a citizen of,

167
00:16:36,080 --> 00:16:40,860
and where it's obviously becoming increasingly difficult to leave,

168
00:16:40,860 --> 00:16:46,240
I think people might be quite reluctant to go to New Zealand or Australia this year,

169
00:16:46,240 --> 00:16:50,680
because at any point we might have more lockdowns,

170
00:16:50,680 --> 00:16:55,120
and you might find that you can travel there, but may find it very difficult to travel back again.

171
00:16:55,120 --> 00:16:58,240
So for this year, I think it's a non-starter.

172
00:16:58,240 --> 00:17:01,660
In the future, I'd like to see it continue.

173
00:17:01,660 --> 00:17:05,920
It's a huge shame that we're going to miss having a race when there is a Worldcon,

174
00:17:05,920 --> 00:17:08,420
potentially in Australia and New Zealand.

175
00:17:08,420 --> 00:17:12,920
But hopefully it can continue in some form in future years.

176
00:17:12,920 --> 00:17:16,340
I do feel sorry for New Zealand 2020,

177
00:17:16,340 --> 00:17:24,720
because even if we completely eradicate the coronavirus before that convention goes ahead,

178
00:17:24,720 --> 00:17:28,400
I can't imagine this is going to do good things to their membership curve.

179
00:17:28,400 --> 00:17:33,660
And as the first Worldcon in New Zealand, I think that is a huge shame.

180
00:17:33,660 --> 00:17:40,540
And I think your point about guff running to Australasia is another facet to that being a huge shame.

181
00:17:40,540 --> 00:17:42,860
But I think hopefully we can,

182
00:17:42,860 --> 00:17:46,440
keep the Fannish connections going online.

183
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:50,100
So should we talk about Consolation?

184
00:17:50,100 --> 00:17:53,880
Are both of you on the Consolation Facebook group?

185
00:17:53,880 --> 00:17:56,760
So I am, but I'm not really reading it.

186
00:17:56,760 --> 00:17:57,480
That's fair.

187
00:17:57,480 --> 00:17:59,040
Because I had the look.

188
00:17:59,040 --> 00:18:02,540
And I don't know,

189
00:18:02,540 --> 00:18:05,800
I think I must have just been in completely the wrong frame of mind.

190
00:18:05,800 --> 00:18:07,940
But I didn't find it very funny.

191
00:18:08,320 --> 00:18:10,680
It started off quite funny,

192
00:18:10,680 --> 00:18:13,220
because it was all full of conrunners.

193
00:18:13,220 --> 00:18:14,760
And conrunners,

194
00:18:14,760 --> 00:18:18,180
the group of people are on like Journeymen of Fandom,

195
00:18:18,180 --> 00:18:21,480
which is the primary Facebook conrunning group,

196
00:18:21,480 --> 00:18:23,320
have a certain mindset.

197
00:18:23,320 --> 00:18:25,820
And they have a lot in common with each other,

198
00:18:25,820 --> 00:18:28,640
even if the sorts of conventions they're running are very different.

199
00:18:29,180 --> 00:18:33,300
But now Consolation has bloomed to about 20,000 people.

200
00:18:33,300 --> 00:18:37,520
